Harvest_notes: Fungus noted as "???": "no mycos -- just two smallish roots and a ton of rhizomorphs following into the soil"
some THETE proto-crust AF, very dry soil AR. High-N mycos (esp. THETE) will probably be gritter than Low-N; hyphae hold dirt.
lots of dead or nearly-dead SUIPU looking mycos w/NM roots protruding. Very little THETE -- collected all i could find for isotopes, but there's non in % pool.
visible SUIPU hyphae in root side
I guess the hyphae oxidize to brown.
Failed split; Lots of THETE hyphae on perlite
Lots of crust both sides; have intercept coloinzation data here
crust everywhere EXCEPT BF, BR (BR has a little crust, but only at top/stem -- crawled from side A)
lots of hyphae. Unambiguous, happy-looking SUIPU.
had thrips damage. Mostly dead, some live SUIPU, plus possibly some mystery fungus as on side B.
fuiting at top F & R compartments. Weird root architecture -- just one huge clump of mycorrhizas (like a bunch of grapes); taking all for % col.

rhizos saved for RNA: FC6106A, 71.07mg tissue (cleaned and patted dry). Frozen at 3:15, also grabbed a few mycos, all stage 3 (48.98mg). No perlite on this tester (high N). Did point-intercept colonization.
this plant is HUGE! Lots of THETE crust AF, some in AR, BF, BR.
don't know where the data sheet is. Inferred fungal state from tin ball/mass data
I didn't note which fungus was here at harvest, but my tins include mycos listed for both sides A and B of this microcosm. I think both were very likely THETE.
v. dry soil in root compartments. "senescent" also includes visible shriveled mycos. Fewer shriveled B than A
lots of hyphae at top BR, dry soil
scope check shows not all THETE roots have mantle, but they all have clamp-y hyphae everywhere, and many have at least patchy mantle.
several dead SUIPU tips with THETE tips growing out.
Batch FC04: Not picking ALL TFRs, just enough for isotopes.
mycos mostly on their way out. "live" = not squishy, live root at tip. "dead" = squishy, oft. coated in hyphae (recycling?)
one tiny SUIPU clump, otherwise NM. Found oNE myco tip in % col dish.

WAS "really happy SUIPU" on 8.21. NOTE: I have, throught this harvest, occasionally seen plants whose mycorrhizas appear to have been eaten like drumsticks. Only the core of each branch remains. Typically SUIPU plants. I suspect soil arhtropod fungivory? This plant has such damage, especially at the top fo the root system.
grabbed some dirty hyphae off top of soil slab
Lots of hyphae visible on soil
hyphae on mesh look like THETE, but saw NO THETE mycos (checked a few tips on compound scope
Found a little THETE hyphae on fungus side, but no obvious mycos. Probably very limited colonization. (Might have been on side A? Not sure.)
just a little. Mycos mostly very young (?) -- look like NM roots, but with hypahe on outside. Mantle is there.
A little THETE crust at top, but I could not find any THETE mycos. (Looked HARD, checked for mantle, found none).
nearly all fine roots have hyphae, but not all. "Uncol" may be early mycos (in own envelope)
kind of pathetic mycos (leggy, not light/swollen)
mycos dark and leggy w/thin, patchy mantle at best. The usual for low N?
I cannot tell old THETE from NM root tips. Sorting into "other %."
v. little fungus evident. I'm noticing black spores on the roots that remind me of rose rust aeciospores.
patches of white saprobe in soil on root side
a couple dead SUIPU tips evident w/NM or young THETE tips growing out. TFRs maybe very young (or old) THETE, but no hyphae visible.

much more hyphae than B, some eating dead fine roots (fuzzed out) (Note: I didn't write down which fungus I found here on the harvest sheet. The preceding comment sure makes it seem like I found THETE on both sides, though, so that's what I'm going with here.)
found 9 mycos total on whole root system, not much hyphae
mycos aren't pretty (mostly leggy and dark), but look okay on compound scope)

fruiting at top. Some hyphae look almost suipu-ish. Lots of NM roots with hyphae clinging. (Young mycos? Yes. looked on compound scope and saw mantle developing at end of these ambiguous young mycos.)
